"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/922363","Ministry of Justice","false","2018-06-20","<p>The Criminal Injuries Compensation Scheme clearly sets out that payments will be refused where the applicant has an unspent conviction specifically excluded by the Scheme. This includes convictions resulting in custodial sentences and community orders.</p><p> </p><p>In 2016/2017, CICA received over 31,000 new claims for criminal injuries compensation. Payments totalling over £142 million were paid out in the same year to victims of violent crime.</p><p> </p><p>The number of applicants who have been refused compensation by the Criminal Injuries Compensation Authority for having an unspent conviction from 1 January to 12 June 2018 is 790.</p><p> </p><p>Providing information about the category of that unspent offence could only be obtained at disproportionate cost.</p>","Charnwood","Edward Argar",,"2018-06-20T14:39:44.663Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/922363/answer","Biography information for Edward Argar","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/922363/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/922363/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2018-06-12","Criminal Injuries Compensation: Disqualification","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many people have been refused compensation by the Criminal Injuries Compensation Authority for having an unspent conviction by category of that unspent offence in 2018 to date.","false","Biography information for Richard Burgon","Leeds East","Richard Burgon","152822"
