"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/922388","Department for Transport","false","2018-06-21","<p>This matter is reserved to the Secretary of State under the terms of the Partnership Agreement. Rail North Ltd has become part of Transport for the North.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2018-06-21T14:47:48.817Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/922388/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/922388/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/922388/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2018-06-12","Northern: Compensation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, whether Transport for the North or Rail North were consulted in respect of any request by Arriva Rail North to be  reimbursed for revenues lost as a result of industrial action; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Ian Mearns","Gateshead","Ian Mearns","152742"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/922389","Department for Transport","false","2018-06-21","<p>We recognise that passengers have faced an unacceptable level of disruption in the North.</p><p> </p><p>A special compensation scheme for inconvenienced passengers is being established and details will be announced by Transport for the North.</p><p> </p><p>This is an industry funded scheme which Network Rail are paying for in full from within their existing operational budgets. Network Rail have accepted that their late completion of upgrades has led to the significant disruption.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2018-06-21T14:55:57.347Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/922389/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/922389/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/922389/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2018-06-12","Northern: Compensation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, on whom the cost of compensating passengers inconvenienced by the emergency timetable introduced on Northern Rail falls.","false","Biography information for Ian Mearns","Gateshead","Ian Mearns","152743"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/922390","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2018-06-18","<p>The 2018 paper (Nuñez-Garcia et al) used data derived from different studies carried out in different countries and under different field and laboratory conditions. This data presented different scenarios to that experienced in Great Britain. Therefore our evidence base for the SICCT test will continue to be based on two recent and bespoke studies (Karolemeas et al. (2012) and Goodchild et al. (2015)), as detailed on the TB Hub website.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2018-06-18T08:59:07.263Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/922390/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/922390/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/922390/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2018-06-12","Bovine Tuberculosis","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what assessment he has made of the accuracy of the analysis in the paper, Meta analyses of the sensitivity and specificity of ante-mortem and post-mortem diagnostic tests for bovine tuberculosis in the UK and Ireland, published in March 2018 that the median sensitivity estimate for the SICCT test is between 49 per cent  and 65 percent; and what the implications are of that analysis for the information contained on the Government-sponsored web site, TB Hub.","false","Biography information for Dr David Drew","Stroud","Dr David Drew","152630"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/922391","Department for Transport","false","2018-06-15","<p>The next review of HS2 Phase One will take place in September 2018, and the Terms of Reference will be agreed with the Infrastructure and Projects Authority over the summer. We do not publish either the terms of reference or the outcomes of these reviews as this would prejudice the safe space for policy formulation.</p>","Wealden","Ms Nusrat Ghani","152622","2018-06-15T07:29:41.85Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/922391/answer","Biography information for Ms Nusrat Ghani","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/922391/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/922391/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2018-06-12","High Speed 2 Railway Line","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, when the next review of High Speed 2 Phase One by the Infrastructure and Projects Authority is planned be undertaken.","false","Biography information for Dame Cheryl Gillan","Chesham and Amersham","Dame Cheryl Gillan","152621"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/922392","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2018-06-21","<p>As part of our oversight of local government expenditure, we consider the financial stability and service delivery of individual authorities, liaising with other departments, including the Department of Health and Social Care in relation to adult social care. On this basis, we have no immediate concerns on the ability of local authorities to fulfil their statutory duties. We recognise the pressures on local government which is why we have provided an additional £2 billion to adult social care over the three years to 2019-20.</p>","Richmond (Yorks)","Rishi Sunak",,"2018-06-21T16:03:56.41Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/922392/answer","Biography information for Rishi Sunak","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/922392/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/922392/answer","Richmond (Yorks)","Rishi Sunak","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/922392/answer/previousversion/63773","Biography information for Rishi Sunak","7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2018-06-12","Social Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, what recent assessment he has made of the ability of local authorities to meet their statutory duties for adult social care.","false","Biography information for Rosie Cooper","West Lancashire","Rosie Cooper","152695"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/922393","Department for Transport","false","2018-06-15","<p>The next review of HS2 Phase One will take place in September 2018, and the Terms of Reference will be agreed with the Infrastructure and Projects Authority over the summer. We do not publish either the terms of reference or the outcomes of these reviews as this would prejudice the safe space for policy formulation.</p>","Wealden","Ms Nusrat Ghani","152621","2018-06-15T07:29:41.913Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/922393/answer","Biography information for Ms Nusrat Ghani","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/922393/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/922393/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2018-06-12","High Speed 2 Railway Line","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what the timetable is for the details of the review of High Speed 2 Phase One to be agreed with the Infrastructure and Projects Authority; and if he will publish those details once so agreed.","false","Biography information for Dame Cheryl Gillan","Chesham and Amersham","Dame Cheryl Gillan","152622"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/922394","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-06-20","<p>The Government recognises the importance of safeguarding the welfare of claimants who have incurred debt. Universal Credit already has procedures and regulations in place protect claimants from excessive deductions. The maximum rate of deductions cannot normally exceed 40% of the Universal Credit standard allowance. If a claimant is in financial difficulty as a result of the level of deductions being made they can contact the Department to request that a reduction in deductions be considered.</p><p>In January 2018, of all Universal Credit Full Service awards:</p><p>(a) 6% had a total deduction amount (either to a third party, for an advance, or for a fraud penalty) which equalled 40 per cent of the standard allowance</p><p>(b) Less than 0.5% had a total deduction amount which exceeded 40 per cent of the standard allowance. In these cases, a priority order is applied so that deductions for rent or fuel costs are applied first, in order to protect claimant welfare.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2018-06-20T16:23:53.597Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/922394/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/922394/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/922394/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-06-12","Universal Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what plans her Department has to introduce a minimum protected income within the universal credit system to ensure that claimants are not left in poverty after any deductions are taken from their monthly award.","false","Biography information for Ian Mearns","Gateshead","Ian Mearns","152744"
